---
import CvtLayout from "../../../layouts/CvtLayout.astro";
---

<CvtLayout title="Architecture — CVT" description="Technical overview of the CVT platform for builders and partners.">
  <section class="section-band max-w-3xl">
    <p class="eyebrow-mono">For technical readers</p>
    <h1 class="display-lg mt-4">Platform architecture</h1>
    <p class="mt-6 leading-relaxed text-body">
      CVT separates immutable facts from versioned interpretation. Registry events flow into
      <code class="code-chip">trust_events</code>;
      the policy engine produces snapshots and passport views filtered by partner tier and consent.
    </p>

    <ul class="mt-8 space-y-3 text-body">
      <li><strong class="text-ink-strong">Event model</strong> — append-only facts; reversals add compensating events</li>
      <li><strong class="text-ink-strong">Policy engine</strong> — versioned trust levels, good standing, dormancy</li>
      <li><strong class="text-ink-strong">APIs</strong> — public passport, partner Soft / Enhanced / Hard search</li>
      <li><strong class="text-ink-strong">Database</strong> — Supabase Postgres; riders registry + trust tables</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="mt-12 space-y-6 border-t border-hairline pt-12 text-body leading-relaxed">
      <h2 class="display-md !text-xl">What CVT is today</h2>
      <p>
        CVT is a Commercial Verification Terminal built first as an admin portal for boda boda rider verification in Uganda. It lets approved staff sign in, register riders, capture consent, upload and review documents, manage verification status, handle complaints, and generate public QR verification profiles. The current MVP is focused on staff/admin workflows: rider lists, rider detail views, complaint management, and placeholder pages for SACCOs, stages, and staff administration. It also supports a demo mode when Supabase isn't configured, so the app can still be explored without live backend setup.
      </p>
      <p>
        It's built with Next.js, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, and Supabase for auth, Postgres, and storage. The design is mobile-first and low-bandwidth aware, and it's explicitly not a ride-hailing app, even though a separate CVT Connect layer can use the registry for dispatch channels like WhatsApp. The system emphasizes auditability, privacy, and role-based access, with stricter controls for sensitive rider data and public verification output.
      </p>

      <h2 class="display-md !text-xl pt-4">What makes it unusual</h2>
      <p>
        CVT is not just a registry — it's being shaped into a broader trust platform. The architecture separates raw verified facts, a versioned Trust Profile, and channel layers like Connect, so the same core record can power public verification, partner searches, and future use cases without rewriting history. That facts-vs-interpretation split keeps immutable events intact while trust level and standing evolve through policy-driven recomputation.
      </p>
      <p>
        It also handles trust and disclosure carefully — avoiding the trap of turning verification into a safety promise or a vague risk score. Instead it uses explainable, positive-dominant trust signals, staged access tiers, consent-bound partner searches, and sealed or moderated records where needed. In plain terms: a serious accountability system, not a dashboard pretending to know who's "safe."
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-10 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/cvt/docs/trust-architecture-v1" class="btn-primary !py-2.5 !text-sm">Trust Architecture v1</a>
      <a href="/cvt/docs/trust-profile" class="btn-outline !py-2.5 !text-sm">Trust Profile spec</a>
      <a href="/cvt/guides/partner-integration" class="btn-outline !py-2.5 !text-sm">API reference</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</CvtLayout>
